{"cursor":"3953","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = name = Francis Richard Gurney Hoare honorific_suffix =\n| native_name = native_name_lang = image = image_size = alt = caption =\n| birth_date = 1879 death_date = 1959 birth_place = England death_place =\n| placeofburial = placeofburial_label = placeofburial_coordinates = \n| nickname = birth_name = allegiance = South Africa branch = South African Air\n| Force serviceyears = rank = Major General servicenumber = unit = commands =\n| Director-General of Technical Services battles = World War I battles_label =\n| awards =  relations = laterwork = signature = website = \n}} Major-General 'Francis Richard Gurney Hoare' (1879-1959) was a South African\nmilitary commander.\n\nBorn in England, and educated at Harrow School, he joined the British Army in\n1894. He served in the Anglo-Boer War, after which he settled\nin the Transvaal as a civil servant. [http://www.national.archives.gov.za National Archives of South\nAfrica]\n\nHe joined the Transvaal Horse Artillery in 1912. Shortly after the outbreak of\nWorld War I in 1914, he was seconded to the British Army as an officer in the\nArmy Ordnance Department. From there he transferred to the Royal Flying Corps in\n1917. He was made a Commander of the Order of the British Empire\nfor his war services.\n\nLt Col Hoare returned to South Africa after the war, and became a founder member\nof the South African Air Force on its formation in 1920. He was Staff Officer\nfor Air Equipment at Defence Headquarters from 1921 to 1933. List of\nOfficers of the Union Defence Forces (1921).\n\nFrom 1933 to 1937, he served as the Union Defence Forces' Director Of Technical\nServices, and was briefly Director of Air and Technical Services (with the rank\nof colonel) before retiring in 1937.\n\nHe returned to active duty in 1939 and served as Director-General of Technical\nServices again from 1939 to 1940. For the rest of World War II, he was involved\nin arms production and procurement. Orpen, N. & Martin, H.J. South\nAfrica at War. He retired again at the end of the war. In 1944, he was\nmade a Companion of the Order of the Bath. London Gazette 36545 (8\nJune 1944).\n","linknr":117,"url":"Francis_Hoare","recorded":1375085416,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Francis_Hoare&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Francis_Hoare&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/South_Africa","/wiki/South_African_Air_Force","/wiki/Major_General","/wiki/World_War_I","/wiki/Companion_of_The_Most_Honourable_Order_of_the_Bath","/wiki/Commander_of_The_Most_Excellent_Order_of_the_British_Empire","/wiki/List_of_South_African_military_chiefs","/wiki/Harrow_School","/wiki/British_Army","#cite_note-sc-1","/wiki/Anglo-Boer_War","/wiki/Transvaal_Province","#cite_note-sc-1","#cite_note-nasa-2","/wiki/Transvaal_Horse_Artillery","/wiki/World_War_I","/wiki/Royal_Flying_Corps","#cite_note-sc-1","/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire","/wiki/South_African_Air_Force","#cite_note-lo-3","/wiki/South_African_National_Defence_Force","#cite_note-sc-1","/wiki/World_War_II","#cite_note-saw-4","/wiki/Order_of_the_Bath","#cite_note-lg-5","/w/index.php?title=Francis_Hoare&action